# Making changes to the `FrankWolfe.jl` on your local machine and publishing them in the official package.

Say, for example, you are working on a project for which you need to implement changes to the `FrankWolfe.jl` package, such as updating existing, or creating new, components. You are working on your project with `git`.
The recommended flow is as follows:

1) `dev FrankWolfe`: allows you to make local changes to the package. Basically, this comand creates a local repository inside your local Julia environment (wherever it is located on your machine), which points to the remote repository at https://zib-iol.github.io/FrankWolfe.jl/dev/.
You can then directly modify your local version of the `FrankWolfe.jl` package;

2) Then, follow the usual git flow with `add`, `commit` and `push` to *your* remote repository;

3) The first time you `push` these changes to your remote repository, this will automatically create a new branch in the official FW repository https://zib-iol.github.io/FrankWolfe.jl/dev/. This branch will keep track of code updates: any time new changes are pushed to your own remote repository, those changes will also appear in this new branch.

4) Once you are finished with modifying the code in the `FrankWolfe.jl` package and are ready to make your changes official, you can ask for a pull request on https://zib-iol.github.io/FrankWolfe.jl/dev/. After the pull request is examined by the main developers of the package, the changes will be published in the `master` branch

Notice that you can undo `dev` by typing `free FrankWolfe`

How to contribute:
